{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"650"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/650"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.57,0.02,0.35,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/650"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26947"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6993"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man attends the Emergency Department with a four day of an increasing headache and a one day history of a constant nasal discharge. The amount of nasal discharge increases when he bends forward. The discharge is a clear colour. One week earlier he had hurt his nose during a game of soccer. After the game he noticed some stuffiness and difficulty in breathing through his right nostril. He reports no loss of consciousness or other changes to his health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is otherwise medically well with no medical conditions, medications or past surgery. He drinks 2-3 glasses of beer on the weekends, and does not smoke or do recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his GCS is 15, vitals are normal, and neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home with general practitioner follow-up","CT head","Admit for observation only","Beta-2 transferrin analysis of nasal discharge","Intra-thecal fluorescein test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has ongoing nasal discharge following head trauma; it is important to rule out a base of skull fracture. The concern is that the nasal discharge is the result of a CSF leak. An impact sufficient enough to cause a CSF leak via a skull base fracture may cause other intracranial injury, so it would be prudent to do a CT head (particularly examining the skull base) first to exclude any other damage and promptly follow this with a sample of the nasal discharge for a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-2 transferrin analysis\u003C/strong\u003E to confirm that its CSF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA beta-2 transferrin analysis of the nasal discharge provides a highly sensitive and selective, non-invasive test for the detection of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leakage in the case of head trauma. However, this test is not rapid and typically takes up to 24 hours to return a result. With the patient\u0027s increasing headache it would be essential to admit the patient to hospital\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Efor clinical observation at least until the result of the beta-2 transferrin returns. \u003Cstrong\u003EObservation only\u003C/strong\u003E without further investigation is not appropriate given the patient\u0027s ongoing symptoms. Likewise, if the patient had any neurological signs, or signs of infection, hospital admission would be wise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient may need surgical intervention if he has a significant CSF leak with a base of skull fracture; thus, \u003Cstrong\u003Edischarging home for GP follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate management plan until a CSF leak is ruled out.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Beta-2-transferrin is a useful test in distinguishing the presence of cerebrospinal fluid in nasal discharge, which indicates a basal skull fracture."],"references":["Ryall RG, Peacock MK, Simpson DA. Usefulness of beta 2-transferrin assay in the detection of cerebrospinal fluid leaks following head injury. J Neurosurg. 1992 Nov;77(5):737-9. doi: 10.3171/jns.1992.77.5.0737. PMID: 1403116.","Simon LV, Newton EJ. Basilar Skull Fractures. [Updated 2020 Nov 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470175/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26947"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"650"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26947"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-28T16:48:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-28T16:48:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"650"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41958"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHead